4/ You can reach out directly to individual customers and employees, bypassing the whole corporate hierarchy in a Tweet.
3/ A single Twitter stream can pool the kind of insight that used to require whole focus groups.
2/ For CEOs, social media can be an executive productivity tool, broadcast channel, source of consumer + competitor intel and PR vehicle.

7/ For a deeper dive, check out my new article in Fast Company: Inside the Social Media Skills Gap https://t.co/LXZJaeQBQR
6/ The fix? Companies (and leaders) need to acknowledge that “social media literacy” is a foundational job skill - and train for it.
5/ And it's true in all departments as social extends thru marketing, sales, customer service, etc. It's part of every function.
4/ It's not just a generational thing either, older employees and millennials alike have a tough time keeping up with social media changes.
3/ This leads not just to embarrassing mistakes, but trillions (yup, trillions) in lost value. The stakes are huge.
2/ 90% of US companies are on social, but according to @HBR only 12% think their employees use it effectively.
1/ We hear a lot about the talent gap today, but have you heard about the social media skills gap?
